{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The first common attitude is that the appropriate method for doing ethics was described by John Rawls when he formulated the reflective equilibrium method.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Another common attitude is that moral philosophy has no method Ð anything goes in ethical theorising as long as the results are significant enough.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "The reflective equilibrium method has its limits and yet not all ways of proceeding in ethics are equally good.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "For this reason, I argue that we need to be more aware of the argumentative strategies we employ in ethics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "This requires being methodologically reflective and transparent and taking part in the debates about the merits and problems of different methodologies exactly in the way done in the chapters of this volume.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "The reflective equilibrium method is easy to outline.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "We must begin from judgments about individual cases which must be held sincerely and which must also be stable in the kind of careful deliberation that is not distorted by strong emotions or self-interested bias.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "In the second stage, we attempt to formulate a set of general moral principles that could both fit and also justify the previous convictions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Finally, in the fourth stage, we fine-tune our principles by taking into consideration the leading ethical theories on the topic and the best arguments made in their support.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "It is easy to see just why the reflective equilibrium is such a promising account of how we ought to do moral philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "It is an ideal that seems provide us with almost something like an algorithm Ð clear steps which anyone should be able to follow systemically in order to achieve moral knowledge.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Despite this, many ethicists have always been torn about the reflective equilibrium method for several reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "One of the most poignant criticisms has always been that, even if when we use the reflective equilibrium method we must begin from our carefully considered moral judgments, these judgments are still bound to be a reflection of cultural indoctrination, superstition and bias.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The reflective equilibrium method also suffers from other problems Ð two of which are relevant here.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Firstly, many ethicists feel like the description of the reflective equilibrium method is not especially helpful when it comes to their everyday work.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The second issue is that very few recent works in moral philosophy employ the reflective equilibrium method in any recognisable and explicit form.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Perhaps these limitations of the reflective equilibrium method have led to another extreme in the ethicistsÕ attitudes towards the methodological questions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The second common methodological attitude is a reflection of Paul FeyerabendÕs (1975) Ôanything goesÕ view in the debates concerning the appropriate methods of science.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "The core idea behind this attitude is the observation that, if we consider both historical and more recent key contributions to moral philosophy, it is difficult to extract a unique method such that its use would explain the fact that these very contributions constitute the most important advances.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "There are several reasons for why this Ômethodological anarchismÕ is not wholly satisfactory either.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "The main problem is that the attitude is based on a presupposition according to which different views in moral philosophy can be evaluated independently of the arguments provided in their support.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Rather, it is much more plausible to think that how plausible different answers to different questions in moral philosophy are is always intertwined with the question of how strong arguments have been provided for those answers.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Let me then draw three lessons from the problems of the methodological attitudes outlined above.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "Firstly, given that moral philosophers investigate very different kinds of questions, it is unlikely that there will be any single method of ethics that could be used to make progress in all debates of moral philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "The second lesson we should draw is that it is unlikely that even the best methods of ethics will be simple step-by-step algorithms, which even a computer could be programmed to follow.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Finally, insofar as we can identify different methods in the previous looser sense, we should resist the idea that all ways of proceeding are equally good.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
